Wine tastings don’t always need to be about expensive cheeses and perfectly aged charcuterie. Sometimes, all you need is a glass of your favorite wine and the perfect crunchy snack. Whether you’re hosting friends or just winding down after a long day, pairing wine with chips or breadsticks is a surprisingly delightful way to elevate snack time.
Here’s your ultimate guide to matching your favorite wines with everyone’s favorite salty sidekicks—chips and breadsticks.

1. Classic Potato Chips + Sparkling Wine or Champagne
There’s something magical about the combo of crispy, salty potato chips and the bubbly elegance of a sparkling wine. The saltiness of the chips balances beautifully with the acidity and fizz of Champagne or a dry Prosecco.
Why it works: The bubbles cleanse the palate after each salty bite, making every sip and crunch feel fresh. It’s simple, classic, and unexpectedly classy.
Snack tip: Go for kettle-cooked chips for a heartier crunch that holds up to bold bubbles.

2. Sea Salt Breadsticks + Sauvignon Blanc
Sauvignon Blanc, known for its zesty citrus notes and herbaceous finish, pairs wonderfully with plain or lightly salted breadsticks. It’s the kind of combo that whispers rather than shouts—but it works.
Why it works: The clean, crisp flavor of the wine highlights the subtle wheatiness of the breadstick without overwhelming it. It’s a great starter for your snack-and-sip session.
Snack tip: Add a side of hummus or tzatziki for dipping, and you’ve got a perfect trio.

3. Barbecue Chips + Zinfandel
Zinfandel’s smoky, jammy, and spicy profile makes it a match made in heaven for barbecue chips. The layers of smoky paprika, brown sugar, and tomato in the chips reflect the wine’s own bold personality.
Why it works: The sweet-savory notes in the chips mirror the dark fruit and pepper of Zinfandel. Each bite and sip enhance the other.
Snack tip: Try a smoky chipotle-flavored chip for an extra kick.

4. Cheese-Flavored Chips (like Cheddar or Nacho) + Chardonnay
Creamy, oak-aged Chardonnays complement cheesy chips in the best way. The richness of the wine stands up to the intense umami of cheddar or nacho cheese flavoring.
Why it works: Think of it as a shortcut to mac & cheese with white wine. The buttery texture of the Chardonnay coats the tongue while balancing the cheese’s sharpness.
Snack tip: Go for baked cheese crisps or a cheddar-seasoned breadstick for a more grown-up twist.

5. Garlic Breadsticks + Chianti or Sangiovese
Italian wines like Chianti are naturally made to be enjoyed with bold, garlicky carbs. Garlic breadsticks pair beautifully with these red wines, thanks to their acidity and earthy undertones.
Why it works: The savory notes in garlic breadsticks bring out the rustic cherry and herbaceous notes in Sangiovese-based wines like Chianti. It’s bold, satisfying, and totally addictive.
Snack tip: Toast your breadsticks with a brush of olive oil and rosemary for even more aromatic impact.

6. Sour Cream & Onion Chips + Dry Rosé
Sour cream & onion is a nostalgic classic with a tangy bite that plays well with a dry rosé. The wine’s crisp acidity and red fruit notes contrast beautifully with the creamy sharpness of the chip.
Why it works: It’s a playful balance of creamy and crisp, with the rosé keeping things light and breezy.
Snack tip: For a more artisanal twist, try rosé with sour cream and chive dip and plain crisps.

Final Sip: Go With What You Love
At the end of the day, there are no hard rules—only suggestions to enhance your snack-and-sip experience. If you love salt and vinegar chips with Malbec, or sesame breadsticks with Riesling, go for it. Pairings are about discovering what lights up your taste buds, not following a sommelier’s rulebook.
So, pop open that bag, pour a glass, and let snack time become wine time. Cheers! 🍷🥖🥔


